WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:12.694
Context includes every token available when the model produces its next response: system instructions, tool definitions, examples, retrieved documents, message history, intermediate results, and the current request.

2
00:00:12.145 --> 00:00:16.700
Context engineering manages that whole state, not just the opening prompt.

3
00:00:16.229 --> 00:00:20.880
Anthropic describes context as finite and subject to diminishing returns.

4
00:00:20.338 --> 00:00:29.297
Research on context rot shows a recurring pattern: as the amount of material grows, models can become less reliable at recalling the relevant item hidden inside it.

5
00:00:28.704 --> 00:00:31.519
A larger window does not make attention free.

6
00:00:31.003 --> 00:00:33.972
This explains why a giant prompt can fail.

7
00:00:33.396 --> 00:00:40.894
The correct rule may be present, yet surrounded by obsolete plans, repeated explanations, raw logs, and edge cases.

8
00:00:40.355 --> 00:00:46.497
The model must infer which parts are current, authoritative, and relevant before it can even solve the task.

9
00:00:46.010 --> 00:00:49.200
Good context engineering is therefore selective.

10
00:00:48.671 --> 00:00:53.294
Before every meaningful step, ask what information changes the next decision.

11
00:00:52.738 --> 00:00:57.524
Keep the goal, necessary constraints, current evidence, and live state.

12
00:00:56.924 --> 00:01:00.806
Move reference detail behind an index when it can be fetched later.

13
00:01:00.312 --> 00:01:02.290
Selection is iterative.

14
00:01:01.770 --> 00:01:05.046
After a tool call, the Agent has new evidence.

15
00:01:04.514 --> 00:01:07.829
After an error, a new boundary becomes important.

16
00:01:07.317 --> 00:01:11.997
After a milestone, raw traces may be replaced by a compact state summary.

17
00:01:11.413 --> 00:01:16.834
The useful context at step ten is not identical to the useful context at step one.

18
00:01:16.338 --> 00:01:18.413
Minimal does not mean short.

19
00:01:17.882 --> 00:01:24.505
A complex migration may need extensive acceptance criteria, repository conventions, and risk controls.

20
00:01:23.957 --> 00:01:29.964
The standard is the smallest set that fully supports the expected behavior, not the fewest possible words.

21
00:01:29.507 --> 00:01:34.582
First, treat context as a finite attention budget rather than unlimited storage.

22
00:01:34.110 --> 00:01:38.300
Second, more tokens can dilute the instruction that matters next.

23
00:01:37.818 --> 00:01:42.306
Third, keep the smallest sufficient set and refresh it as the task changes.
